<section xml:id="C30.S6">
<title>Functions of Complex Argument</title>        
 
 
<para xml:id="C30.S6.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C30.S6.p1.s1">
The solutions <Math equation-number="30.6.1" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S6.E1">\mathit{Ps}^{m}_{n}\left(z,\gamma^{2}\right),\mathit{Qs}^{m}_{n}\left(z,\gamma^{2}\right),</Math> of (30.2.1) with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S6.p1.m3">\mu=m</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S6.p1.m4">\lambda=\lambda^{m}_{n}\left(\gamma^{2}\right)</Math> are real when <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S6.p1.m5">z\in(1,\infty)</Math> , and their principal values (§4.2(i)) are obtained by analytic continuation to <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S6.p1.m6">\mathbb{C}\setminus(-\infty,1]</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C30.S6.Px1">
<title>Relations to Associated Legendre Functions</title>   
<para xml:id="C30.S6.Px1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C30.S6.Px1.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="30.6.2" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S6.E2">\mathit{Ps}^{m}_{n}\left(z,0\right)=P^{m}_{n}\left(z\right),\mathit{Qs}^{m}_{n}\left(z,0\right)=Q^{m}_{n}\left(z\right);</Math> compare §14.3(ii).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C30.S6.Px2">
<title>Wronskian</title>   
<para xml:id="C30.S6.Px2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C30.S6.Px2.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="30.6.3" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S6.E3">\mathscr{W}\left\{\mathit{Ps}^{m}_{n}\left(z,\gamma^{2}\right),\mathit{Qs}^{m} _{n}\left(z,\gamma^{2}\right)\right\}=\frac{(-1)^{m}(n+m)!}{(1-z^{2})(n-m)!}A_ {n}^{m}(\gamma^{2})A_{n}^{-m}(\gamma^{2}),</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S6.Px2.p1.m1">A_{n}^{\pm m}(\gamma^{2})</Math> as in (30.11.4).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C30.S6.Px3">
<title>Values on <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S6.Px3.m1">(-1,1)</Math></title>   
<para xml:id="C30.S6.Px3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C30.S6.Px3.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="30.6.4" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S6.E4">\mathit{Ps}^{m}_{n}\left(x\pm\mathrm{i}0,\gamma^{2}\right)=(\mp\mathrm{i})^{m} \mathsf{Ps}^{m}_{n}\left(x,\gamma^{2}\right),</Math> , <Math equation-number="30.6.5" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S6.E5">\mathit{Qs}^{m}_{n}\left(x\pm\mathrm{i}0,\gamma^{2}\right)={(\mp\mathrm{i})^{m }\left(\mathsf{Qs}^{m}_{n}\left(x,\gamma^{2}\right)\mp\tfrac{1}{2}\mathrm{i} \pi\mathsf{Ps}^{m}_{n}\left(x,\gamma^{2}\right)\right)}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C30.S6.Px3.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C30.S6.Px3.p2.s1">
For further properties see Arscott (1964b).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C30.S6.Px3.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C30.S6.Px3.p3.s1">
For results for Equation (30.2.1) with complex parameters seeMeixner and Schäfke (1954).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
</section>
